{{Italic title|reason=.}}
'''La plume de ma tante''' ({{lang-fr|"my aunt's quill"}}) is a phrase in popular culture, attributed to elementary French language instruction (possibly as early as the 19th century<ref name="TeschnerEvans2007">{{cite book|author1=Richard V. Teschner|author2=Eston Earl Evans|title=Analyzing the Grammar of English|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fij1OwTBS4EC&pg=RA2-PA9|accessdate=30 October 2012|date=15 May 2007|publisher=Georgetown University Press|isbn=978-1-58901-166-3|pages=2–}}</ref>) and used as an example of grammatically correct phrases with limited practical application that are sometimes taught in introductory foreign language texts. As [[Life (magazine)|''Life'' magazine]] said in 1958, "As every student knows, the most idiotically useless phrase in a beginner's French textbook is ''la plume de ma tante'' (the pen of my aunt)."<ref name="Inc1958">{{cite journal|title=Frisky French Fun on Broadway|journal=Life|date=8 December 1958|page=67|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Yz8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA67#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=26 April 2014}}</ref> The phrase is also used to refer to something deemed completely irrelevant.<ref name="Beeby-Lonsdale1996">{{cite book|author=Allison Beeby-Lonsdale|title=Teaching Translation from Spanish to English: Worlds Beyond Words|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qW2kiADQhHQC&pg=PA10|accessdate=30 October 2012|date=1 January 1996|publisher=University of Ottawa Press|isbn=978-0-7766-0399-5|pages=10–}}</ref> The term lent its name to the musical play ''[[La Plume de Ma Tante]]'', which won a [[Tony Award]] in 1959.

The phrase is also used in teaching and remembering the sounds of the French vowel ''a''; '''La plume de ma tante''' contains three instances of ''a'' that use two different pronunciations. Other limited-use phrases used as pronunciation guides include: '''Le petit bébé est un peu malade''' ({{lang-fr|"the little baby is slightly ill"}}), which contains six variants of ''e'', and '''Un bon vin blanc''' ({{lang-fr|"a good white wine"}}), which contains four nasal vowels.

The phrase's French converse is [[:fr:My tailor is rich|''my tailor is rich'']], the first in the original English [[Assimil]] guide.

In the 1973 film ''[[The Exorcist (film)|The Exorcist]]'', [[Linda Blair]]'s character utters the phrase as she is possessed. In 1982, [[Del Boy]] from the TV show ''[[Only Fools and Horses]]'' says it to a policewoman in the first episode of the second season. 

